00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:11.830
DNA.

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:12.717
PRESENTER 2: Hi.

00:04:12.717 --> 00:04:14.550
So probably should have
written on the board

00:04:14.550 --> 00:04:17.380
the project previously
known as DNA,

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.760
because we've completely
reskinned our game.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.000
So it's no longer about
a biology type thing.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.330
It's about exploring space.

00:04:26.330 --> 00:04:30.010
So DNA is now the name
of your mothership,

00:04:30.010 --> 00:04:35.640
And we're going to put you
as a small spaceship-- RINA,

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:37.610
so R-I-N-A, basically.

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:39.140
RNA.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:41.990
And your goal is to travel
across different planets

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:45.360
and eventually make it
back to your mothership

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:48.663
before running out
of fuel or exploding

00:04:48.663 --> 00:04:50.370
on a bunch of asteroids.

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:52.320
So our game has two
primary mechanics

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:53.780
that we're working on.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:56.140
First is a menu-type
screen where

00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:58.350
you can see different
planets that you

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:01.626
can head towards on your
way back to your mothership.

00:05:01.626 --> 00:05:04.250
And each planet would tell you--
if you hover over each planet,

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:08.080
it will tell you, at this
planet you can pick up X fuel,

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:12.510
or you can get this
jet boost type thing.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:17.570
And so the strategy comes from
the planning for which planet

00:05:17.570 --> 00:05:20.860
to go to relative to
the other planets.

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:24.050
And the trade-offs also come
with which planet do you go to,

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:27.860
or what do you pick
up at each planet.

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:30.510
And the other mechanic is
actually getting to the planet.

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:33.130
So using a stat boost and/or
fuel that you picked up

00:05:33.130 --> 00:05:38.490
from each planet, you have to
navigate through a platform,

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:39.675
or not really a platform.

00:05:39.675 --> 00:05:43.430
More like Flappy Bird
or a Copter type level,

00:05:43.430 --> 00:05:46.960
where your stats
increase, like how fast

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:49.320
you go through the level
or how maneuverable you are

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:52.097
and how you can avoid obstacles.

00:05:52.097 --> 00:05:53.805
So our game has two
mechanics, and that's

00:05:53.805 --> 00:05:55.660
what we're kind of
working on right now.

00:05:55.660 --> 00:06:00.480
We have the moving from one
level to the next motion part

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.940
down, so now we're working
mainly on balancing the game

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:06.750
and seeing what should
the stat caps be,

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:08.280
or what should the
starting caps be,

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:10.010
so it's not too boring
at the beginning,

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:13.970
but it's also not too
hard at the very end.

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:16.945
And our backlog
has a lot of art.

00:06:16.945 --> 00:06:17.820
PROFESSOR: Thank you.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:25.010
Ghost Maze.

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:27.790
PRESENTER 3: So for Ghost
Maze, our design for the game

00:06:27.790 --> 00:06:28.870
hasn't changed much.

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:31.190
We solidified our
original idea, is

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:36.700
that you're going to start off
in the middle of a dark maze

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:39.270
and you have very
limited visibility.

00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:41.720
You're going to explore
the graph, or the maze,

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:45.580
and basically find the
exit that leads you out

00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:47.940
of this dark scary place.

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:51.040
You have a sanity
bar that goes down

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:52.770
the more you are in the dark.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:57.409
And you have the
ability to increase

00:06:57.409 --> 00:06:58.950
the brightness of
your lantern, which

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:02.300
would give you a higher radius
of visibility or decrease it,

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:03.510
which would make it lower.

00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:06.710
But the higher it
is, the less slowly

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:10.080
your sanity goes out, but the
faster that your battery dies.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:12.730
So you want to
optimize for that--

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:17.730
how fast can I explore this
maze versus how slowly do

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:19.900
I need my sanity to drop.

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:22.491
And you can completely
have it off if you want,

00:07:22.491 --> 00:07:23.490
because they're battery.

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:28.590
But that would be chipping away
from your sanity much faster.

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:33.200
There's ghosts in the
maze, so you can't just

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:37.775
do the bug around strategy,
which would always guarantee

00:07:37.775 --> 00:07:39.240
you to get out of a maze.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:44.060
But there's going to be ghosts
at strategic, random positions.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:46.490
These ghosts were
originally intended

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:50.160
to have AI that would have
them find you or attack you

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:51.070
or whatever.

00:07:51.070 --> 00:07:52.790
But we changed it
so that they're just

00:07:52.790 --> 00:07:56.030
patrolling in a
predetermined pattern

00:07:56.030 --> 00:08:01.402
so that you can focus on the
one mechanic of the game, which

00:08:01.402 --> 00:08:03.110
is moving around and
finding a good path,

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:08.040
as opposed to escaping
from things chasing you.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:10.830
The one change we made, the
biggest change we made so far

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:13.980
is we switched from
Flixel to Unity 2D

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:16.420
because we couldn't
get Flixel running

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.080
on most of the computers
we had, and it just

00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:21.500
brought so many complications.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:24.747
So we ended up
switching to Unity 2D.

00:08:24.747 --> 00:08:25.622
PROFESSOR: Thank you.

00:08:29.665 --> 00:08:30.270
Score High.

00:08:33.819 --> 00:08:35.929
PRESENTER 4: So
Score High focused

00:08:35.929 --> 00:08:37.734
on simplifying our game.

00:08:37.734 --> 00:08:39.900
We realized we were probably
overextending ourselves

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:41.630
with the number of
features we wanted.

00:08:41.630 --> 00:08:44.214
So even though our
goal stayed the same,

00:08:44.214 --> 00:08:45.630
we kind of simplified
it, and I'll

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:46.850
talk about that in a minute.

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:50.910
So Score High's goal is to
survive the week of school.

00:08:50.910 --> 00:08:53.416
If you can do well, even better.

00:08:53.416 --> 00:08:55.570
And that becomes difficult
because as a player,

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:57.360
you have your stats to maintain.

00:08:57.360 --> 00:08:59.540
You need sleep,
and you need food.

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:01.680
But you also need to
not fail your classes

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:04.260
and get kicked out, so
you need to do your work.

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:08.240
So the main features of the
game are you play your stats,

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:10.715
so how are you doing as
a person, your schedule,

00:09:10.715 --> 00:09:13.720
which is going to list your
classes and what PSETs are due

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:16.210
and when they're due,
and then also the map.

00:09:16.210 --> 00:09:18.310
You, as a character,
go around the map,

00:09:18.310 --> 00:09:21.590
and you have to go to certain
buildings to do your work.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:25.530
And as I said, the trade-offs
are managing you internally,

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:27.520
so you have to go to
your dorm to sleep,

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:29.940
but your PSET might
be due in two minutes,

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:31.900
and if you don't
run across campus,

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:35.406
will you be able to get it
done and pass your class?

00:09:35.406 --> 00:09:38.559
In terms of updates, I
think that's about it.

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:40.056
Thank you.

00:09:40.056 --> 00:09:43.530
PROFESSOR: Thank you.

00:09:43.530 --> 00:09:45.050
Build a Space Car.

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:47.650
PRESENTER 5: So originally
we were Build a Car,

00:09:47.650 --> 00:09:50.080
but we decided that the game
would be better in space,

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:51.530
so now it's Build a Space Car.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:53.960
The idea is that you have
some kind of spaceship

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:55.480
that you need to
add components to,

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:57.237
and then you send
it out on a mission.

00:09:57.237 --> 00:09:59.320
Out on this mission, it'll
run into random events,

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:01.304
and you'll get a report
of what happened.

00:10:01.304 --> 00:10:03.290
And then it'll come
back and you need

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:04.998
to iterate, add more
components to either

00:10:04.998 --> 00:10:07.390
make it faster or stronger
or have more attack.

00:10:07.390 --> 00:10:10.950
And then that way, you'll be
able to succeed on missions.

00:10:10.950 --> 00:10:13.875
The trade-offs come into
what components do you add,

00:10:13.875 --> 00:10:16.722
and what effect does that have
on the stats of your spaceship,

00:10:16.722 --> 00:10:18.430
and the fact that the
more components you

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.110
add to your spaceship,
the more it costs

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.735
and the less money
you're going to make

00:10:21.735 --> 00:10:23.430
from going out on that mission.

00:10:23.430 --> 00:10:26.710
The main product
backlog features

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:30.380
that we have are the things
like adding components to ships,

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:33.102
coming up with stats for
all of the components

00:10:33.102 --> 00:10:36.600
that we have in the game,
and designing a system where

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:39.190
the ship will go
out on missions,

00:10:39.190 --> 00:10:40.730
get some results
from all of that,

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:44.679
and then loop back into
this initial building phase.

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:45.665
PROFESSOR: Thank you.

00:10:48.623 --> 00:10:51.950
And MIT Sim.

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:54.520
PRESENTER 6: All right.

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:57.740
So the idea of our game is
we play as an unnamed dean

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:59.560
for student life at MIT.

00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:02.642
And you make and manage
the decisions at MIT,

00:11:02.642 --> 00:11:04.975
and you have to trade-off all
of these various resources

00:11:04.975 --> 00:11:07.060
that you have, like student
happiness and the endowment

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:07.560
and whatnot.

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:10.050
And you have to please the
MIT president above you

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:13.000
and the MIT
corporation above them.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.260
And then you also have to
please the parents of students

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:18.235
who might hear of some
crazy things happening

00:11:18.235 --> 00:11:20.410
and you have to respond to them.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:24.890
So for example, you might make
shoes mandatory on campus.

00:11:24.890 --> 00:11:27.810
And suddenly East
Campus revolts.

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:29.330
But maybe it improves
your standing

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:30.816
with the parents or something.

00:11:30.816 --> 00:11:33.782
So that's the general
gist for our game, yeah.

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:42.990
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:11:42.990 --> 00:11:46.150
So it's good to hear that people
are both refining and changing

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:48.600
