00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:21.075
of this game.

00:30:21.075 --> 00:30:22.950
Maybe it's targeted at
the buyer of the game,

00:30:22.950 --> 00:30:25.339
but certainly not
at the people who

00:30:25.339 --> 00:30:27.630
are going to have the most
difficulty playing this game

00:30:27.630 --> 00:30:29.950
even though the game
is intended for them.

00:30:29.950 --> 00:30:31.340
By the way, this
is a great game.

00:30:31.340 --> 00:30:35.040
This is a whole lot of
fun to play with family.

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:40.970
So a lot of what I'm going
to discuss going forward

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:44.527
is just kind of a theoretical
analysis of that process

00:30:44.527 --> 00:30:45.610
that we just went through.

00:30:45.610 --> 00:30:48.570
We just used a whole
bunch of different cues,

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:52.090
just looking at the
box and the pieces,

00:30:52.090 --> 00:30:57.680
and the text on the box and the
colors and cultural knowledge

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:00.512
to be able to figure out how
it is that you play this game.

00:31:00.512 --> 00:31:01.720
Now, this is a game for kids.

00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:02.928
It's not a very complex game.

00:31:02.928 --> 00:31:05.700
If I gave you some sort
of really, really abstract

00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:08.120
German board game, where
everything are cubes--

00:31:08.120 --> 00:31:09.930
and there are many,
many games just

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:11.850
fitting that description--
you'd probably

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:13.420
have to read the
instructions just

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:17.450
to be able to figure out
how to play the game.

00:31:17.450 --> 00:31:19.400
But ideally, you'd
want the experience

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:21.479
to be about as
easy as the process

00:31:21.479 --> 00:31:23.520
that we just walked through
with this board game.

00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:26.170
You look at this game, you're
presented with information

00:31:26.170 --> 00:31:29.332
upon launching it or even before
you bought it, and by the time

00:31:29.332 --> 00:31:31.040
you've actually started
playing the game,

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:33.870
you already have a sense of
what you're going to expect,

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:38.460
which sets people up to
learn the more complex things

00:31:38.460 --> 00:31:41.450
that you need to teach
them along the way.

00:31:41.450 --> 00:31:44.442
Now, there's a book-- which I
should have brought upfront.

00:31:46.980 --> 00:31:48.980
This book I strongly
recommend, The Design

00:31:48.980 --> 00:31:52.570
of Everyday Things, which
was previously titled

00:31:52.570 --> 00:31:54.810
The Psychology of
Everyday Things,

00:31:54.810 --> 00:31:57.850
because that's really
what this is all about.

00:31:57.850 --> 00:32:01.970
Usability, designing for
usability and you are testing

00:32:01.970 --> 00:32:04.600
usability, you are
asking questions

00:32:04.600 --> 00:32:07.050
about the player's psychology.

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:10.220
And you are trying to use
that to your advantage

00:32:10.220 --> 00:32:13.240
to be able to help them
understand how to manipulate

00:32:13.240 --> 00:32:16.880
your game and how to get the
experience that you want out

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:18.165
of it without being confused.

00:32:18.165 --> 00:32:21.110
Now, there's this model
that Donald Norman,

00:32:21.110 --> 00:32:25.160
the author off this book,
goes into great detail.

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:31.070
And it says, there are
goals, there's an intention

00:32:31.070 --> 00:32:35.870
that the person using an HCI,
a Human Computer Interaction

00:32:35.870 --> 00:32:36.950
system.

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:39.150
And that person has
some sort of goal.

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:40.910
They are using
Excel because they

00:32:40.910 --> 00:32:43.560
want to balance their budget
or something like that.

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:45.111
They have an intention.

00:32:45.111 --> 00:32:47.360
They're going to put numbers
into the spreadsheet that

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:50.740
reflect their actual spending.

00:32:50.740 --> 00:32:52.157
They have a plan,
which is they're

00:32:52.157 --> 00:32:53.739
going to collect all
of their receipts

00:32:53.739 --> 00:32:55.450
together and look at
those bottom lines

00:32:55.450 --> 00:32:56.574
and start typing them in.

00:32:56.574 --> 00:32:57.990
And then they
actually execute it.

00:32:57.990 --> 00:32:59.531
They're actually--
all right, I think

00:32:59.531 --> 00:33:01.130
this is the way how it works.

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:03.690
And then the computer
gives them some sort

00:33:03.690 --> 00:33:07.120
of feedback-- visual,
audio, vibration,

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:09.390
if you're designing a game.

00:33:09.390 --> 00:33:12.780
The person using the system
has to perceive it and then

00:33:12.780 --> 00:33:15.930
figure out what that means.

00:33:15.930 --> 00:33:19.200
OK, a dialog box
popped up on my screen.

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:21.910
I did something peculiar
and didn't expect that,

00:33:21.910 --> 00:33:24.450
and then they have to evaluate,
did that get them any closer

00:33:24.450 --> 00:33:26.110
to the goals that they had.

00:33:26.110 --> 00:33:28.040
And maybe then the
goal changes to maybe

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:31.320
I should learn Excel before I
try to balance my spreadsheet.

00:33:31.320 --> 00:33:36.430
And then now they have a
slightly different goal.

00:33:36.430 --> 00:33:40.240
So you can translate
that into games.

00:33:40.240 --> 00:33:41.530
You start off with the goal.

00:33:41.530 --> 00:33:42.550
How do I win this game?

00:33:42.550 --> 00:33:43.550
How do I lose this game?

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:46.800
How do I avoid losing, and
how do I win this game,

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:48.030
or at least complete it?

00:33:48.030 --> 00:33:51.580
And then the player decides,
what do I want to do

00:33:51.580 --> 00:33:54.360
and comes up with a
plan, which is how am I

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:58.120
going to do that thing that I
want to do, and then tries it.

00:33:58.120 --> 00:34:01.480
The game reacts, gives some
sort of feedback-- audio, sound,

00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:04.390
vibration, whatever--
but the player

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:06.110
still has to perceive it.

00:34:06.110 --> 00:34:08.739
And this is a big
point right there.

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:11.590
If you give the player
feedback and the player

00:34:11.590 --> 00:34:14.540
doesn't perceive that feedback
because they're too distracted

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:16.960
by something else, because
it's the wrong color

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:19.590
or it's off in the
corner of the screen

00:34:19.590 --> 00:34:22.530
where the player isn't
looking, the player

00:34:22.530 --> 00:34:24.034
doesn't get that feedback.

00:34:24.034 --> 00:34:25.659
The player has to
perceive the feedback

00:34:25.659 --> 00:34:27.889
and then figure out
what that means.

00:34:27.889 --> 00:34:30.020
It's like, oh, a big
giant exclamation mark

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:32.017
appeared on the screen.

00:34:32.017 --> 00:34:32.850
What does that mean?

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:35.299
I have no idea.

00:34:35.299 --> 00:34:37.340
And even if a player
understands what that means,

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:38.923
they have to figure
out whether that's

00:34:38.923 --> 00:34:42.310
getting them any closer or
further away from the goals.

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:47.658
So here's an example, back
to my StarCraft fandom.

00:34:47.658 --> 00:34:48.699
You're playing StarCraft.

00:34:48.699 --> 00:34:51.550
You wanted a giant army to
roll over your opponent.

00:34:51.550 --> 00:34:54.610
And that's the goal.

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:58.080
Actually, the goal is just
to roll over your opponent.

00:34:58.080 --> 00:34:59.660
And what do I want to do?

00:34:59.660 --> 00:35:02.240
I want to build a giant army
to accomplish that goal.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:03.510
How do I do that?

00:35:03.510 --> 00:35:05.470
I'm going to build
lots of buildings

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:08.590
that is going to create
all of these army units.

00:35:08.590 --> 00:35:11.570
And those army units are
going to serve that purpose

00:35:11.570 --> 00:35:13.450
that I just described.

00:35:13.450 --> 00:35:14.450
All right, let's try it.

00:35:14.450 --> 00:35:16.330
Game reacts, and you get this.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:20.450
What do I see or hear?

00:35:20.450 --> 00:35:23.040
The computer is yelling at me,
saying not enough minerals.

00:35:23.040 --> 00:35:23.890
What does that mean?

00:35:23.890 --> 00:35:26.620
I guess I need minerals.

00:35:26.620 --> 00:35:29.710
And is that what I want?

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:30.280
I guess.

00:35:30.280 --> 00:35:33.430
If I have minerals, then
I can build those things

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:36.370
that will get me the army that
I want to roll over my opponent.

00:35:36.370 --> 00:35:39.920
All right, my goal hasn't
changed at these long term,

00:35:39.920 --> 00:35:41.470
but my short term goal has.

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:46.440
Now I have to figure out
how to get more minerals.

00:35:46.440 --> 00:35:49.980
So in The Design
of Everyday Things,

00:35:49.980 --> 00:35:54.750
Donald Norman introduces this
concept called affordances.

00:35:54.750 --> 00:35:58.470
And the idea is that there are
certain kinds of interfaces,

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:00.990
things around in the world,
among the machines that you

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:03.850
use every day but
also within games,

00:36:03.850 --> 00:36:07.920
that encourage you to interact
with them in a certain way.

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:14.140
If you see, for
instance, a glass wall,

00:36:14.140 --> 00:36:19.510
and your goal is
to vandalize it,

00:36:19.510 --> 00:36:22.420
what's the most natural thing
to do to that glass wall?

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:24.030
You smash it.

00:36:24.030 --> 00:36:24.570
All right.

00:36:24.570 --> 00:36:27.630
What if it was made
out of plywood,

00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:30.240
and your goal is
to vandalize it?

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:33.120
You want to write on it.

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:35.490
What else can do
with a plywood wall?

00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:36.200
Concrete wall?

00:36:39.990 --> 00:36:41.800
You want to break it?

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:45.610
Or spraypaint-- yeah, yeah
because concrete holds

00:36:45.610 --> 00:36:47.240
paint pretty well.

00:36:47.240 --> 00:36:49.950
So there are these materials
that already suggest things

00:36:49.950 --> 00:36:51.680
that you can do with them.

00:36:51.680 --> 00:36:54.830
And you can take that concept
further in a more explicitly

00:36:54.830 --> 00:36:56.080
designed way.

00:36:56.080 --> 00:36:58.824
So let's look at door handles.

00:36:58.824 --> 00:37:00.490
We've got some door
handles around here.

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:03.150
I guess there is this
kind of crash bar.

00:37:03.150 --> 00:37:04.810
You've got this
sort of door handle,

00:37:04.810 --> 00:37:07.120
and it's just the right
size for your hand.

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:09.500
It's kind of curled
in a pleasant way that

00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:13.020
affords gripping, that affords
turning because there is

00:37:13.020 --> 00:37:16.550
a hinge on one side, and
there's a sort of a lever action

00:37:16.550 --> 00:37:19.210
so you can use less force to
be able to turn this thing.

00:37:19.210 --> 00:37:21.025
So you are
immediately encouraged

00:37:21.025 --> 00:37:22.410
to gripping this thing.

00:37:22.410 --> 00:37:25.450
But what does this door handle
not tell you about the door?

00:37:25.450 --> 00:37:28.560
It's very important if
you want to open the door.

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:32.630
Yeah, do you push or
do you pull this door?

00:37:32.630 --> 00:37:37.470
So let's think of different
kinds of door handles.

00:37:37.470 --> 00:37:42.320
This is something that
you could grab and pull.

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:48.720
But the designers of these
intended to use this for you

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:50.470
to push, because it's
a lot easier for you

00:37:50.470 --> 00:37:54.260
to exert force going
outwards than to exert force

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:57.740
going inwards, using
this kind of bar.

00:37:57.740 --> 00:38:01.450
That's why you see these on
doors that open outwards.

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:04.834
However, that's still a problem
because there's a little rod

00:38:04.834 --> 00:38:06.250
all the way through,
and your hand

00:38:06.250 --> 00:38:08.180
can go all the way around it.

00:38:08.180 --> 00:38:11.240
And it's still tempting to just
grab the thing and pull it,

00:38:11.240 --> 00:38:14.780
which is a really bad situation
if it's an outward turning

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:16.340
fire escape, for instance.

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:19.092
You don't want people
trying to pull a door open

00:38:19.092 --> 00:38:21.550
when they should be pushing it
when they're in an emergency

00:38:21.550 --> 00:38:22.390
situation.

00:38:22.390 --> 00:38:25.320
You don't want to have them
do that kind of processing.

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:28.810
So that's why they came
up with these crash bards.

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:31.640
And eventually this one,
which is very similar to what

00:38:31.640 --> 00:38:34.130
we have on our door.

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:37.680
They have these very wide
bars that you can push,

00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:40.532
and you can put your hand
around it but not comfortably.

00:38:40.532 --> 00:38:42.740
It's much easier for you to
use the flat of your hand

00:38:42.740 --> 00:38:44.470
to be able to push it outwards.

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:48.350
And the version that we have
on this store over there,

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:51.960
the part that you push is off
to one side, which tells you

00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:54.840
where you should be putting
your hands so that you can get

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:57.130
better leverage to open the
door-- which way the door

00:38:57.130 --> 00:38:58.730
opens, left or right.

00:38:58.730 --> 00:39:00.370
And that's the
kind of thing that

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:02.430
automates this
process of how do I

00:39:02.430 --> 00:39:05.170
open this door in an
emergency situation.

00:39:05.170 --> 00:39:08.120
These are affordances
of the design itself.

00:39:08.120 --> 00:39:10.807
The material is mostly
metal, although I

00:39:10.807 --> 00:39:13.390
guess the version that I've got
up here has a rubberized grip.

00:39:13.390 --> 00:39:14.870
And the idea of
a rubberized grip

00:39:14.870 --> 00:39:17.810
is that, well, maybe you want
to put your hand on the rubber

00:39:17.810 --> 00:39:20.620
part, not on the metal part.

00:39:20.620 --> 00:39:23.190
So you can design these
things in your games,

00:39:23.190 --> 00:39:25.580
these affordances to
sort of encourage people

00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:28.110
to, say, click on something.

00:39:28.110 --> 00:39:30.180
You can design
something that's meant

00:39:30.180 --> 00:39:32.140
to be clicked on to
look like a button,

00:39:32.140 --> 00:39:33.790
for instance, that's
slightly raised.

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:36.710
And Apple does this a
lot, especially if you

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:39.200
look at the older iOS design.

00:39:39.200 --> 00:39:43.730
Every single little icon kind
of had this little glossy bump.

00:39:43.730 --> 00:39:46.400
It tried to give you
this impression that this

00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:48.016
was something that
was raised off

00:39:48.016 --> 00:39:50.390
the screen, even though of
course it was completely flat.

00:39:50.390 --> 00:39:52.890
And it tried to encourage you
that this was a thing that you

00:39:52.890 --> 00:39:55.310
can tap with your finger.

00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:57.242
I'll go into more
examples of this later.

00:39:57.242 --> 00:39:58.950
Anyone can think of
something that you've

00:39:58.950 --> 00:40:02.140
seen in a computer
interface that encourages

00:40:02.140 --> 00:40:04.300
you to use it in that way?

00:40:04.300 --> 00:40:05.290
It could be mechanical.

00:40:05.290 --> 00:40:08.910
It could be on screen.

00:40:08.910 --> 00:40:11.330
Look at your
computers right now.

00:40:15.668 --> 00:40:18.506
AUDIENCE: It's not like
this on Mac anymore,

00:40:18.506 --> 00:40:20.006
but the scroll
baller has a little--

00:40:20.006 --> 00:40:21.934
I don't know what you call it,
the lines that look like you

00:40:21.934 --> 00:40:22.975
can grab them and scroll.

00:40:22.975 --> 00:40:25.560
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
it had a texture,

00:40:25.560 --> 00:40:28.260
sort of three little lines
that sort of gave you

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:31.900
the idea that this was a
raised thing for gripping,

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:34.230
in the same way that a
rubberized grip over a door

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:36.920
handle encourages you
to put your hand on it.

00:40:36.920 --> 00:40:39.380
It probably would make more
sense nowadays, actually,

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:43.050
given that so much of it
has gone to touch screens.

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:44.730
The scroll wheel
would be another one.

00:40:44.730 --> 00:40:46.730
I just broke my mouse
scroll wheel this morning,

00:40:46.730 --> 00:40:48.220
so it's on my mind.

00:40:51.520 --> 00:40:53.010
Now, scroll wheels
on mice actually

00:40:53.010 --> 00:40:54.010
do two different things.

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:56.080
You can click them, and
you can rotate them.

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:58.170
But they're kind of really
designed to be rotated.

00:40:58.170 --> 00:40:59.795
And that's why I
broke my scroll wheel,

00:40:59.795 --> 00:41:03.160
because I kept clicking it.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:05.650
You are encouraged to roll
that thing up and down.

00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:09.100
They're usually made out of
some sort of rubberized material

00:41:09.100 --> 00:41:15.110
and a place right where
your finger has easy reach.

00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:19.060
You can flip that around and
make things deliberately hard

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.670
when you don't want someone
to be doing something.

00:41:21.670 --> 00:41:29.190
Here's a screenshot
of-- what game is this?

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:30.370
Plants vs. Zombies.

00:41:30.370 --> 00:41:35.330
There are no zombies on
screen, but it's very popular.

00:41:35.330 --> 00:41:40.250
And early in the game, early in
the development of this game,

00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:44.665
they had different values
for these early items

00:41:44.665 --> 00:41:46.290
that you'll get right
in the beginning.

00:41:46.290 --> 00:41:49.940
This is I think the very first
level in the entire game,

00:41:49.940 --> 00:41:52.240
and they're just trying to
get you to play this game.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:54.190
Now, this is a
tower defense game.

00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:57.380
You plant plants
that do various kinds

00:41:57.380 --> 00:41:58.920
of offensive or
defensive attacks

00:41:58.920 --> 00:42:01.090
against zombies who
are invading your lawn

00:42:01.090 --> 00:42:05.320
and trying to get
into your house.

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:10.310
And there are things like
sunflowers that actually create

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:12.660
the energy that you
need to be able to power

00:42:12.660 --> 00:42:15.270
the rest of your plants and
to give you the resources

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:17.890
to be able to put the
rest of your plants down.

00:42:17.890 --> 00:42:22.780
But if the game
starts like this,

00:42:22.780 --> 00:42:27.350
what is first a first time
player who's encountering

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:28.590
this game likely to do?

00:42:32.510 --> 00:42:33.980
AUDIENCE: Put a
plant in the dirt.

00:42:33.980 --> 00:42:35.438
PROFESSOR: Put a
plant in the dirt.

00:42:35.438 --> 00:42:36.972
Which plant?

00:42:36.972 --> 00:42:38.424
AUDIENCE: A sunflower.

00:42:38.424 --> 00:42:40.340
PROFESSOR: You think to
put a sunflower first?

00:42:44.768 --> 00:42:46.603
AUDIENCE: Or the pea shooter.

00:42:46.603 --> 00:42:47.228
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:47.228 --> 00:42:47.970
The one on the left is--

00:42:47.970 --> 00:42:49.170
PROFESSOR: The pea shooter.

00:42:49.170 --> 00:42:50.170
AUDIENCE: Left to right.

00:42:50.170 --> 00:42:50.878
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:42:50.878 --> 00:42:52.390
If they read it
from left to right,

00:42:52.390 --> 00:42:55.090
then they'll probably start
with the one on the left.

00:42:55.090 --> 00:42:56.940
Maybe there's a
50/50 chance at least

00:42:56.940 --> 00:42:58.820
that they will put
the pea shooter first,

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:00.530
which is the little green guy.

00:43:00.530 --> 00:43:03.230
And that's actually
going to get the player

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:05.680
into a lot of trouble real
fast, because once they

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:09.264
put that plant down,
they can't do anything

00:43:09.264 --> 00:43:11.180
for a really, really
long time, by which point

00:43:11.180 --> 00:43:12.700
you may have lost the game.

00:43:12.700 --> 00:43:14.870
They need to put the
sunflower down first.

00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:18.320
So designers recognized,
oh OK, so we could just

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:19.550
flip things around.

00:43:19.550 --> 00:43:22.319
But again, there's a 50%
chance that they will just

00:43:22.319 --> 00:43:22.860
get it wrong.

00:43:22.860 --> 00:43:24.360
At it's the first
level of the game.

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:28.070
You don't want to turn somebody
off the game that quickly.

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:31.120
So what they did
was they reduced

00:43:31.120 --> 00:43:35.380
the cost of the sunflower
and started you off

00:43:35.380 --> 00:43:37.900
with just enough money to
actually plant that sunflower.

00:43:37.900 --> 00:43:39.420
They didn't actually
flip the cards around

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:40.690
because they figured,
that doesn't really

00:43:40.690 --> 00:43:41.552
solve the problem.

00:43:41.552 --> 00:43:43.010
What they did was
that they made it

00:43:43.010 --> 00:43:44.310
so that the only
thing that you can

00:43:44.310 --> 00:43:45.726
do at the beginning
of the game is

00:43:45.726 --> 00:43:48.480
plant that sunflower,
because that's pretty much

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:51.700
always the right thing
to do in this game.

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:54.680
Now, the cost reduction
might have been also

00:43:54.680 --> 00:43:57.120
out of other game
balance considerations.

00:43:57.120 --> 00:43:59.370
Maybe they decided, wow,
we really overpriced

00:43:59.370 --> 00:44:00.169
those sunflowers.

00:44:00.169 --> 00:44:02.460
We should make them a little
bit easier for you to get.

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:06.610
But this also serves
a usability system.

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:08.080
They want the people
to understand,

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:10.420
the first thing that you
do on any level, plant

00:44:10.420 --> 00:44:11.180
that sunflower.

00:44:11.180 --> 00:44:14.510
Now, they could have told you
that, but this is a constraint.

00:44:14.510 --> 00:44:16.340
They've made it
impossible for a player

00:44:16.340 --> 00:44:18.715
to do the wrong thing right
at the beginning of the game.

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:24.690
However, as the
game goes on, this,

00:44:24.690 --> 00:44:26.530
and due to game
balance issues, they

00:44:26.530 --> 00:44:28.730
started to come up
with other plants.

00:44:28.730 --> 00:44:32.710
This thing is called a walnut,
this brown thing over there.

00:44:32.710 --> 00:44:33.600
It makes a wall.

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:35.710
It looks like a nut.

00:44:35.710 --> 00:44:38.470
And they figured through
game balance, well,

00:44:38.470 --> 00:44:41.940
it's pretty much got to
be about 50 solar energy,

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:44.920
so we're going to have to price
it the same as the sunflower.

00:44:44.920 --> 00:44:47.160
But we don't want players
putting down walls

00:44:47.160 --> 00:44:48.368
at the beginning of the game.

00:44:48.368 --> 00:44:49.630
They don't actually need to.

00:44:49.630 --> 00:44:52.890
They should still be
putting sunflowers.

00:44:52.890 --> 00:44:56.599
So the solution
that they had was,

00:44:56.599 --> 00:44:59.140
they have these recharge meters
that fill up from the bottom.

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:01.431
You can sort of see that this
is right at the beginning

00:45:01.431 --> 00:45:04.010
of the game when you've got a
lot of different kind of plants

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:05.190
that you can plant.

00:45:05.190 --> 00:45:07.750
But only the sunflower
is fully charged up,

00:45:07.750 --> 00:45:09.520
and it's the only
card that you can use.

00:45:09.520 --> 00:45:12.750
The rest of them are slowly
filling up over time.

00:45:12.750 --> 00:45:15.231
Right in the first, maybe,
five seconds of the game,

00:45:15.231 --> 00:45:16.980
there is no other card
that you can plant,

00:45:16.980 --> 00:45:19.800
even though the costs
may imply that you

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:21.360
can afford to plant
the walnut right

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:22.568
at the beginning of the game.

00:45:22.568 --> 00:45:23.170
You can't.

00:45:23.170 --> 00:45:25.410
You have to plant the sunflower.

00:45:25.410 --> 00:45:28.120
So again, they've
made it impossible

00:45:28.120 --> 00:45:29.630
for you to do the wrong thing.

00:45:29.630 --> 00:45:32.470
There's also that shovel, but
you can't use the shovel right

00:45:32.470 --> 00:45:33.175
at the beginning of the game.

00:45:33.175 --> 00:45:35.050
The shovel right at the
beginning of the game

00:45:35.050 --> 00:45:38.390
has no effect because you
haven't planted anything.

00:45:38.390 --> 00:45:39.480
So that's a constraint.

00:45:39.480 --> 00:45:42.950
That's preventing someone
from doing the wrong thing.

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:44.725
Now, if the decision
of whether you

00:45:44.725 --> 00:45:46.100
do the right thing
or wrong thing

00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:49.260
is a major game play
issue and it's something

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:52.230
that you want people to sort
of agonize and to decide over,

00:45:52.230 --> 00:45:53.730
then you don't want
to constrain it.

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:57.090
You want to give them the
option of making that mistake.

00:45:57.090 --> 00:46:00.210
But if it's an issue
of learnability,

00:46:00.210 --> 00:46:04.330
if making the wrong decision
makes your game hard to learn

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:06.410
and hard to figure out
how to even get ahead

00:46:06.410 --> 00:46:08.100
and how to make
progress in the game,

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:10.410
or even understand
how your game works,

00:46:10.410 --> 00:46:12.890
then that's something that you
should consider doing things

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:15.790
like constraints and use
affordances to sort of suggest,

00:46:15.790 --> 00:46:19.400
this is what you should do,
constraints to demonstrate

00:46:19.400 --> 00:46:22.522
what you shouldn't do.

00:46:22.522 --> 00:46:24.210
Now, that's affordances
and constraints.

00:46:24.210 --> 00:46:25.187
Any questions so far?

00:46:32.820 --> 00:46:33.600
All right.

00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:35.930
There are other things
that you can do in addition

00:46:35.930 --> 00:46:38.640
to affordances and constraints
that sort of suggest

00:46:38.640 --> 00:46:41.000
how something should be used.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:42.940
So this is from Minecraft.

00:46:42.940 --> 00:46:45.700
And how many of you
have played Minecraft?

00:46:45.700 --> 00:46:50.360
OK, about a quarter
of the class.

00:46:50.360 --> 00:46:54.790
This is something that you see
really early on in the game.

00:46:54.790 --> 00:46:57.070
The way how Minecraft
is played, you

00:46:57.070 --> 00:47:00.230
are dropped off in a sort
of wilderness environment.

00:47:00.230 --> 00:47:02.006
Everything's made up of blocks.

00:47:02.006 --> 00:47:03.880
So it's kind of like a
wilderness environment

00:47:03.880 --> 00:47:04.924
made out of LEGOs.

00:47:04.924 --> 00:47:06.340
And the only thing
that you can do

00:47:06.340 --> 00:47:08.680
is walk around and punch things.

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:11.790
So you start punching the ground
and you get some dirt blocks

00:47:11.790 --> 00:47:12.420
out of it.

00:47:12.420 --> 00:47:14.369
You start punching
trees, and you

00:47:14.369 --> 00:47:16.160
start getting some wood
blocks out of them,

00:47:16.160 --> 00:47:18.800
and they go into your inventory.

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:21.960
What you very
quickly discover, I

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:24.050
would say, in the first
minute of game play,

00:47:24.050 --> 00:47:26.250
is that if you went
into your inventory

00:47:26.250 --> 00:47:28.730
and looked at those
blocks, you can move them

00:47:28.730 --> 00:47:32.585
into this little four-by-four
square, just using your mouse

00:47:32.585 --> 00:47:33.960
and clicking and dragging them.

00:47:33.960 --> 00:47:38.640
And the square is
named crafting.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:43.420
So OK, I've beat up 15 trees.

00:47:43.420 --> 00:47:45.352
So now I've got
15 blocks of wood.

00:47:45.352 --> 00:47:46.310
What do I do with them?

00:47:46.310 --> 00:47:49.390
Well, if I drag them into the--
I can turn them into planks.

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:50.260
Is it planks?

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:54.640
Yeah, planks-- just by
dragging them up there.

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:55.370
OK.

00:47:55.370 --> 00:47:58.880
By dragging things
into the crafting box,

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:00.800
I can make other
kinds of things.

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:02.860
That's the craft
part of Minecraft.

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:06.070
The mining part is the
punching part of the world.

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:09.410
So you punch the world,
and you make planks.

00:48:09.410 --> 00:48:13.552
You put planks into the crafting
square, and you get sticks.

00:48:13.552 --> 00:48:15.010
And you can do all
kinds of things,

00:48:15.010 --> 00:48:19.600
like make torches and make
arrows and so on and so forth.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:24.720
Later in the game, you
encounter something--

00:48:24.720 --> 00:48:28.940
you discover that you can
make a crafting table.

00:48:28.940 --> 00:48:32.510
And you see a nine-by-nine
square instead

00:48:32.510 --> 00:48:33.630
of a four-by-four square.

00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:38.991
Because you've already
seen the first one,

00:48:38.991 --> 00:48:41.240
you've already seen this
four-by-four square, the word

00:48:41.240 --> 00:48:44.110
crafting, and the arrow
which points to the right,

00:48:44.110 --> 00:48:47.160
and now you're seeing this very,
very similar thing over here,

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:49.140
and inventory is
still visible there,

00:48:49.140 --> 00:48:51.610
even though it's not
just you anymore, it's

00:48:51.610 --> 00:48:55.059
you and this crafting
table, the implication

00:48:55.059 --> 00:48:56.850
is that you should
interact with this table

00:48:56.850 --> 00:49:00.540
pretty much in the same way that
you interact with objects back

00:49:00.540 --> 00:49:02.780
when you were examining
your inventory.

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:05.020
So this is context that
has been established

00:49:05.020 --> 00:49:07.057
to the previous things
that you're seeing.

00:49:07.057 --> 00:49:08.640
And the things that
you see around it,

00:49:08.640 --> 00:49:12.180
like the arrow and your
arrangement of the boxes.

00:49:12.180 --> 00:49:16.490
And the word crafting-- you're
sort of telling the player,

00:49:16.490 --> 00:49:19.060
treat this very
much in the same way

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:21.510
that you solved that
previous problem.

00:49:21.510 --> 00:49:23.280
And then eventually
you get to make things

00:49:23.280 --> 00:49:28.270
like pickaxes, for instance--
so giving some context to what

00:49:28.270 --> 00:49:29.260
the players are doing.

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:33.840
Now, there's one particularly
powerful kind of context

00:49:33.840 --> 00:49:37.260
that you can set for any action
that a player does in the game.

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:38.870
And some of your
games already have

00:49:38.870 --> 00:49:41.950
this-- and that's some sort
of storyline or setting

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:44.100
or narrative, some sort
of fictional setting

00:49:44.100 --> 00:49:46.240
that your game is
taking place in.

00:49:46.240 --> 00:49:51.050
And often this is done
very, very poorly in games.

00:49:51.050 --> 00:49:53.580
You are being told your
games are in space,

00:49:53.580 --> 00:49:57.450
and you're being encouraged
to walk outside your spaceship

00:49:57.450 --> 00:49:59.340
without a spacesuit or
something like that.

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:01.470
And in your game, that's fine.

00:50:01.470 --> 00:50:04.530
You have no asphyxiation
mechanic or something

00:50:04.530 --> 00:50:05.420
like that.

00:50:05.420 --> 00:50:07.680
But players don't
necessarily assume

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:12.450
that they should be able to walk
outside in space and not die.

00:50:12.450 --> 00:50:14.560
So when you choose
your settings,

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:19.222
when you choose your-- when
you choose your storylines,

00:50:19.222 --> 00:50:20.680
you have to make
sure that they are

00:50:20.680 --> 00:50:22.164
supporting those
kinds of mechanics

00:50:22.164 --> 00:50:23.080
that you come in with.

00:50:23.080 --> 00:50:25.130
A lot of your games started
off by what mechanic

00:50:25.130 --> 00:50:27.660
that you wanted to do.

00:50:27.660 --> 00:50:30.700
Make sure that your storylines
are actually supporting that.

00:50:30.700 --> 00:50:33.500
Can you think of any games,
commercial games for instance

00:50:33.500 --> 00:50:36.000
that you've played, where
the storyline was really

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.400
at odds with what the
players were actually

00:50:38.400 --> 00:50:41.320
being asked to do.

00:50:41.320 --> 00:50:43.130
I see some nods.

00:50:43.130 --> 00:50:45.720
Some hands?

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:47.190
Let's call out a few bad ones.

00:50:47.190 --> 00:50:51.030
AUDIENCE: Well, one this
is that most-- playing

00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:52.907
games, especially
Japanese ones, tend

00:50:52.907 --> 00:50:54.990
do have battle systems
that have basically nothing

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:58.205
to do with the story and have
a lot of strange mechanics

00:50:58.205 --> 00:50:59.482
that aren't actually related.

00:50:59.482 --> 00:51:01.690
For example, the Final
Fantasy games-- your character

00:51:01.690 --> 00:51:04.530
can summon these really powerful
monsters, but for some reason

00:51:04.530 --> 00:51:06.684
you never actually use
those to solve your problems

00:51:06.684 --> 00:51:08.100
in the storyline,
for some reason.

00:51:08.100 --> 00:51:09.390
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:51:09.390 --> 00:51:12.150
And I would say that's
actually the difference

00:51:12.150 --> 00:51:15.020
between the better and the
worse Final Fantasy games.

00:51:15.020 --> 00:51:18.690
In the better Final
Fantasy games,

00:51:18.690 --> 00:51:20.580
they actually explain
why that doesn't work.

00:51:20.580 --> 00:51:23.280
In the worse Final Fantasy
games, you have all this power.

00:51:23.280 --> 00:51:27.420
Why aren't you just solving
the problem instantly?

00:51:27.420 --> 00:51:28.490
That's a good one.

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:30.169
Any others?

00:51:30.169 --> 00:51:34.001
AUDIENCE: Well, I feel like
the classic example is probably

00:51:34.001 --> 00:51:39.280
Skyrim, where you're a warrior
fated to this grand destiny

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:44.759
and probably just run around
punching chickens for a while.

00:51:44.759 --> 00:51:46.594
PROFESSOR: Well, I'm
trying to remember.

00:51:46.594 --> 00:51:49.010
Skyrim, you start off like a
prisoner or something, right?

00:51:51.810 --> 00:51:54.420
But I do remember some of
the earlier Elder Scrolls

00:51:54.420 --> 00:51:55.710
and a lot of Western RPGs.

00:51:55.710 --> 00:51:58.931
It's like, let's go into
the tunnels and kill rats,

00:51:58.931 --> 00:52:00.180
because you're the chosen one.

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:06.590
It comes up.

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:12.210
That is actually, I think,
partly fiction against fiction.

00:52:12.210 --> 00:52:15.632
It's like, you have the quest
which tells you to kill rats.

00:52:15.632 --> 00:52:17.840
And you have the overall
storyline that's telling you

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:20.470
that you're the savior
of the universe.

00:52:20.470 --> 00:52:23.820
And that's at odds.

00:52:23.820 --> 00:52:26.080
But there are mechanical
issues as well.

00:52:26.080 --> 00:52:31.630
Why is your savior
of the universe

00:52:31.630 --> 00:52:33.650
picking up all the cheese
wheels in the world,

00:52:33.650 --> 00:52:39.300
for instance, which
does happen in Skyrim.

00:52:39.300 --> 00:52:43.550
Something else that you can do
is expose more of your system.

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:46.170
How many of you are playing
Destiny right now, by the way?

00:52:46.170 --> 00:52:47.350
Just out of curiosity.

00:52:47.350 --> 00:52:48.100
A few hands, OK.

00:52:51.130 --> 00:52:56.570
One thing that Destiny does
that Halo-- how many of you

00:52:56.570 --> 00:52:58.060
have played Halo?

00:52:58.060 --> 00:52:59.780
OK, more.

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:02.940
One thing that Destiny
does that Halo doesn't do

00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:05.710
is that it actually shows you
how much damage you're putting

00:53:05.710 --> 00:53:07.150
up with every single shot.

00:53:07.150 --> 00:53:09.870
A little floating number,
in a very RPG-like way,

00:53:09.870 --> 00:53:15.350
showing you how effective
your weapon is being.

00:53:15.350 --> 00:53:21.190
And that seems to be a necessary
consideration by Bungie,

00:53:21.190 --> 00:53:24.400
who made both games, that,
well, even though our games kind

00:53:24.400 --> 00:53:28.260
of play in the same way, we need
to reveal this extra little bit

00:53:28.260 --> 00:53:31.640
of information, because the
way how weapons work in Destiny

00:53:31.640 --> 00:53:37.660
is a little bit less predictable
than how they work in Halo.

00:53:37.660 --> 00:53:40.280
So we're actually
just going to show you

00:53:40.280 --> 00:53:43.170
how much damage each weapon
does every time you shoot it

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:46.230
by showing you the
numerical amount.

00:53:46.230 --> 00:53:48.990
This is a screenshot
from SimCity.

00:53:48.990 --> 00:53:51.250
And one of the neat
things about SimCity

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:55.746
is that you can kind of open
the hood on all of the variables

00:53:55.746 --> 00:53:57.620
that the game is tracking
at any given times,

00:53:57.620 --> 00:54:00.750
and they show you these
lovely little bar graphs.

00:54:00.750 --> 00:54:04.767
I think this is, like,
citizen satisfaction or maybe

00:54:04.767 --> 00:54:05.600
it's property value.

00:54:05.600 --> 00:54:07.840
I'm not sure.

00:54:07.840 --> 00:54:10.580
But you can go into all
of these different modes

00:54:10.580 --> 00:54:12.920
where you can look at your
city through different lenses

00:54:12.920 --> 00:54:14.461
to see all of the
different variables

00:54:14.461 --> 00:54:16.790
that the game is tracking
and how they're interacting.

00:54:16.790 --> 00:54:19.590
So it takes a lot of
work to be able to reveal

00:54:19.590 --> 00:54:20.880
this sort of information.

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:23.832
And if you're not careful, you
can reveal so much information

00:54:23.832 --> 00:54:26.290
that a player is just confused
because there's so much data

00:54:26.290 --> 00:54:28.050
on the screen at once.

00:54:28.050 --> 00:54:33.530
But being clear on this is
the action that you're taking

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:36.220
and this is the result,
or here are all the things

00:54:36.220 --> 00:54:39.930
that the game
currently cares about,

00:54:39.930 --> 00:54:42.600
is one way to help
people better understand

00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:45.919
how your game is working,
so opening up the hood

00:54:45.919 --> 00:54:46.460
a little bit.

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:48.400
I don't mean giving
them the source code.

00:54:48.400 --> 00:54:50.040
No one's going to read that.

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.140
I mean putting things on
screen or through audio

00:54:53.140 --> 00:54:56.140
to better reveal what's
happening numerically

00:54:56.140 --> 00:54:56.880
in your game.

00:55:01.180 --> 00:55:03.320
Previous user experience,
we focus-- yes?

00:55:03.320 --> 00:55:06.314
AUDIENCE: What about
the danger of you

00:55:06.314 --> 00:55:08.809
revealing that information,
the player seeing how something

00:55:08.809 --> 00:55:12.135
works, and then them saying,
I don't like how this works,

00:55:12.135 --> 00:55:14.310
I don't want to do this anymore?

00:55:14.310 --> 00:55:17.240
PROFESSOR: Then I think you
have a play-testing issue

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:18.770
to consider.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:23.190
It's not like the player is
confused about the situation.

00:55:23.190 --> 00:55:27.550
The question is-- that there
are two possible answers.

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:30.950
One, maybe our game system is
badly tuned or badly designed

00:55:30.950 --> 00:55:31.850
in the first place.

00:55:31.850 --> 00:55:34.830
And yeah, once people
realize how this game works,

00:55:34.830 --> 00:55:36.910
they're not going to
want to play it anymore,

00:55:36.910 --> 00:55:38.650
which is a game design issue.

00:55:38.650 --> 00:55:41.570
And then the other
situation which

00:55:41.570 --> 00:55:47.550
is, well, if we never explained
these numbers to them,

00:55:47.550 --> 00:55:49.555
they will actually
better like our game.

00:55:49.555 --> 00:55:51.430
Even if they figure out
how this game worked,

00:55:51.430 --> 00:55:52.840
by not showing
them these numbers,

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:53.970
they better like this game.

00:55:53.970 --> 00:55:55.440
I have that issue with
Destiny, actually.

00:55:55.440 --> 00:55:56.856
I don't want to
see those numbers.

00:55:59.220 --> 00:56:01.710
And you can make that
decision to hide it.

00:56:01.710 --> 00:56:03.530
It's like, this is
complexity that we don't

00:56:03.530 --> 00:56:05.955
want players to care about.

00:56:05.955 --> 00:56:07.580
You guys have to be
very, very careful,

00:56:07.580 --> 00:56:12.141
but that's why design is an
interesting, tough problem.

00:56:12.141 --> 00:56:13.640
But those are the
kinds of decisions

00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:15.100
you get to make as a designer.

00:56:18.565 --> 00:56:19.555
Other questions?

