01:02:10.245 --> 01:02:12.160
AUDIENCE: Grants wishes.

01:02:12.160 --> 01:02:14.940
PROFESSOR: Grants your wishes.

01:02:14.940 --> 01:02:15.920
Programs?

01:02:15.920 --> 01:02:17.450
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:17.450 --> 01:02:18.520
PROFESSOR: Like, apps.

01:02:18.520 --> 01:02:20.192
Yeah, OK.

01:02:20.192 --> 01:02:20.900
Some other hands?

01:02:20.900 --> 01:02:22.395
Some other ideas?

01:02:22.395 --> 01:02:23.020
AUDIENCE: Help.

01:02:23.020 --> 01:02:24.103
PROFESSOR: You think help?

01:02:24.103 --> 01:02:26.660
Yeah, you rub the
genie for help.

01:02:26.660 --> 01:02:29.670
So we have three
fairly plausible

01:02:29.670 --> 01:02:32.680
entirely different
interpretations

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:34.240
of what that magic lamp is.

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:35.670
This is an indirection metaphor.

01:02:35.670 --> 01:02:38.430
Everything on this
desktop-- and we

01:02:38.430 --> 01:02:40.910
still use that
terminology today.

01:02:40.910 --> 01:02:43.990
This is from the early '90s.

01:02:43.990 --> 01:02:46.090
Every single one
of these things is

01:02:46.090 --> 01:02:50.300
a metaphor for something else
that you can use on the PDA.

01:02:50.300 --> 01:02:52.430
You're not going to
be writing postcards

01:02:52.430 --> 01:02:58.940
using a digital device because
that's a medium that exists

01:02:58.940 --> 01:03:00.457
outside of digital technology.

01:03:00.457 --> 01:03:02.040
But you're going to
be sending emails,

01:03:02.040 --> 01:03:05.550
so you're going to use that
postcard icon in the middle

01:03:05.550 --> 01:03:08.345
to send messages.

01:03:08.345 --> 01:03:11.950
Are you going to be
sending faxes exactly?

01:03:11.950 --> 01:03:13.510
That's a fax machine.

01:03:13.510 --> 01:03:16.350
First of all, in 2014,
I'm not entirely sure

01:03:16.350 --> 01:03:19.140
whether anyone recognizes
a fax machine anymore.

01:03:19.140 --> 01:03:21.900
Are you going to be using that
thing to make phone calls,

01:03:21.900 --> 01:03:24.360
or are you going to be
sending pictures with it?

01:03:24.360 --> 01:03:28.635
The clock is not such a
difficult thing to understand.

01:03:28.635 --> 01:03:31.050
So some of these
interaction metaphors work,

01:03:31.050 --> 01:03:33.600
and some of them don't.

01:03:33.600 --> 01:03:35.440
Again, if you put
story in your game

01:03:35.440 --> 01:03:41.760
or even some sort of a fantasy
setting or fictional setting,

01:03:41.760 --> 01:03:45.070
that's already establishing
a metaphor for your game.

01:03:45.070 --> 01:03:47.710
If your game is
about child grows up

01:03:47.710 --> 01:03:51.470
and learns to battle
the evils of the world,

01:03:51.470 --> 01:03:53.630
for instance, that
maps on pretty closely

01:03:53.630 --> 01:03:55.750
to the mechanics
of a lot of games.

01:03:55.750 --> 01:03:59.550
That's why the Zelda
franchise works kind of hand

01:03:59.550 --> 01:04:03.090
in hand, the storyline
and the mechanic.

01:04:03.090 --> 01:04:05.210
You start off as this
kind of helpless kid,

01:04:05.210 --> 01:04:07.860
and then you get
all of these tools

01:04:07.860 --> 01:04:09.650
and take on bigger
and bigger challenges.

01:04:09.650 --> 01:04:13.750
It's a big metaphor
for growing up.

01:04:13.750 --> 01:04:19.060
But you can also confuse, or at
the very least, date your game

01:04:19.060 --> 01:04:22.190
by over-relying on metaphors.

01:04:22.190 --> 01:04:25.890
So if you, say, have a big stop
sign or something that, well,

01:04:25.890 --> 01:04:27.570
that's probably pretty timeless.

01:04:27.570 --> 01:04:31.950
But it's going to assume that
everyone has seen a stop sign,

01:04:31.950 --> 01:04:34.100
and your users will be
unclear whether that

01:04:34.100 --> 01:04:38.560
means stop the current action
or stop forward velocity.

01:04:38.560 --> 01:04:41.790
Those are two different things.

01:04:41.790 --> 01:04:45.140
So I'm just saying, be careful
of using too many metaphors

01:04:45.140 --> 01:04:49.274
to do the heavy lifting on
getting your concepts across.

01:04:49.274 --> 01:04:50.690
Often you're going
to have to rely

01:04:50.690 --> 01:04:53.564
on multiple means of
feedback to help people

01:04:53.564 --> 01:04:54.855
understand how your game works.

01:04:58.040 --> 01:05:00.860
Now, one thing that you're
going to be keeping your eye out

01:05:00.860 --> 01:05:04.380
for when you're designing for
usability errors-- mistakes

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:06.910
that people are making,
but I want to clarify there

01:05:06.910 --> 01:05:09.000
are two different
kinds of errors,

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:10.840
and mistakes are
only one of them.

01:05:10.840 --> 01:05:14.050
Slips are skilled
behavior errors.

01:05:14.050 --> 01:05:17.890
Someone who knows what they
want to do and accidentally

01:05:17.890 --> 01:05:19.060
did the wrong thing.

01:05:19.060 --> 01:05:24.710
How many of you
have gone to class

01:05:24.710 --> 01:05:27.676
when you had intended to
go to a friend's dorm room,

01:05:27.676 --> 01:05:29.960
and you just ended
up in your class?

01:05:29.960 --> 01:05:31.360
OK, yeah.

01:05:31.360 --> 01:05:35.450
Or driven to work
or something while

01:05:35.450 --> 01:05:39.140
intending to drive to
your friend's house?

01:05:39.140 --> 01:05:42.535
So it's not like you didn't
know where your friends were.

01:05:42.535 --> 01:05:43.910
You knew where
your friends were,

01:05:43.910 --> 01:05:45.534
and you knew that
you were going there.

01:05:45.534 --> 01:05:48.870
But somewhere along, your skill
behavior of getting to class

01:05:48.870 --> 01:05:51.150
just automatically took over.

01:05:51.150 --> 01:05:53.030
And you did the wrong thing.

01:05:59.070 --> 01:06:01.750
I have calling your boyfriend
by your last boyfriend's

01:06:01.750 --> 01:06:03.240
name on my examples here.

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:05.190
That's a tricky one.

01:06:09.810 --> 01:06:11.670
But things like
clicking a button that

01:06:11.670 --> 01:06:13.753
looks very similar to the
button that you actually

01:06:13.753 --> 01:06:14.580
wanted to click.

01:06:14.580 --> 01:06:16.350
This is, by the way,
something that you

01:06:16.350 --> 01:06:19.540
find in Dark Souls and many,
many different fantasy games,

01:06:19.540 --> 01:06:21.540
is you have a
monster that happens

01:06:21.540 --> 01:06:23.270
to look like a treasure chest.

01:06:23.270 --> 01:06:24.410
And this was intentional.

01:06:24.410 --> 01:06:30.090
So the game designer is using
this kind of player error

01:06:30.090 --> 01:06:33.354
deliberately to sort of trick
you into a powerless position.

01:06:33.354 --> 01:06:34.270
Ooh, a treasure chest.

01:06:34.270 --> 01:06:35.330
I'm going to open it.

01:06:35.330 --> 01:06:37.310
And it bites you.

01:06:37.310 --> 01:06:39.500
So it's going to mimic.

01:06:39.500 --> 01:06:47.360
And those are things that might
be OK to leave in your game.

01:06:47.360 --> 01:06:49.810
If it happens too often,
it can be frustrating,

01:06:49.810 --> 01:06:52.590
especially if you're sort
of designing your user

01:06:52.590 --> 01:06:56.200
interface in a way that
leads people to confusion,

01:06:56.200 --> 01:07:00.090
and you want to be able to catch
those errors and fix those.

01:07:00.090 --> 01:07:03.540
But a little bit harder to
fix are mental model errors,

01:07:03.540 --> 01:07:07.250
where somebody actually thinks
your game works differently

01:07:07.250 --> 01:07:08.804
from how your game
actually works,

01:07:08.804 --> 01:07:10.970
and they're going to make
a mistake because of that.

01:07:10.970 --> 01:07:13.750
So how many of you play Portal?

01:07:13.750 --> 01:07:14.956
All right.

01:07:14.956 --> 01:07:18.100
Up until you meet
this thing, is there

01:07:18.100 --> 01:07:20.280
anything in the game that
can actually hurt you?

01:07:27.112 --> 01:07:28.190
Oh, yeah.

01:07:28.190 --> 01:07:31.340
You can fall into water,
that really, really

01:07:31.340 --> 01:07:32.600
icky-looking water.

01:07:32.600 --> 01:07:34.360
So that's the
first time you die.

01:07:34.360 --> 01:07:36.026
But that's something
that you fall into.

01:07:36.026 --> 01:07:38.510
That's something you
kind of like-- yeah,

01:07:38.510 --> 01:07:42.570
you can kill yourself, but
you have to kill yourself.

01:07:42.570 --> 01:07:45.760
Then you meet these
things, and you

01:07:45.760 --> 01:07:48.930
haven't met a single thing
that is out to get you.

01:07:48.930 --> 01:07:51.000
And then you walk
around the corner,

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:52.950
and what does this thing do?

01:07:52.950 --> 01:07:54.330
AUDIENCE: It gets you.

01:07:54.330 --> 01:07:55.575
PROFESSOR: It gets you.

01:07:55.575 --> 01:07:57.090
It shoots you.

01:07:57.090 --> 01:07:58.550
It's a turret.

01:07:58.550 --> 01:08:01.140
It says some really, really
cute things, and then it's like,

01:08:01.140 --> 01:08:02.230
are you still there?

01:08:02.230 --> 01:08:03.063
Bum-bum-bum-bum-bum.

01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:07.750
And then you suddenly
realize in this game

01:08:07.750 --> 01:08:10.540
that there are things out
there who are actively

01:08:10.540 --> 01:08:13.520
going to be trying to hurt
you even if you're not

01:08:13.520 --> 01:08:15.690
moving, for instance.

01:08:15.690 --> 01:08:20.340
So now, up until that point
in the game, the player

01:08:20.340 --> 01:08:24.439
will be perfectly
legitimately thinking,

01:08:24.439 --> 01:08:27.910
the only way that I'm going
to lose or die in this game

01:08:27.910 --> 01:08:32.899
is to make a mistake
myself or to deliberately

01:08:32.899 --> 01:08:36.460
cause myself to be in a position
that's going to kill me.

01:08:36.460 --> 01:08:39.340
But then they find these things,
and they realize, no, actually,

01:08:39.340 --> 01:08:41.485
there are hostile
elements in this game that

01:08:41.485 --> 01:08:42.720
are out to get me.

01:08:42.720 --> 01:08:44.733
And now they have to
revise that understanding

01:08:44.733 --> 01:08:46.024
of what this game is all about.

01:08:49.734 --> 01:08:50.859
Now, this is the challenge.

01:08:50.859 --> 01:08:53.109
You as a designer,
you are the people

01:08:53.109 --> 01:08:54.290
who are making the games.

01:08:54.290 --> 01:08:56.640
You are making these
systems that players

01:08:56.640 --> 01:08:57.779
are going to interact with.

01:08:57.779 --> 01:08:59.920
And when players are
playing the game,

01:08:59.920 --> 01:09:03.090
they're sort of having a little
conversation with the system.

01:09:03.090 --> 01:09:06.170
But your conversation with
the system is kind of one way.

01:09:06.170 --> 01:09:08.310
You are making this
system, and then

01:09:08.310 --> 01:09:10.890
the system isn't there
to tell you, by the way,

01:09:10.890 --> 01:09:14.060
the players are
doing this thing that

01:09:14.060 --> 01:09:16.639
clearly indicates that you don't
understand what's going on.

01:09:16.639 --> 01:09:18.680
But the system isn't going
to be able to give you

01:09:18.680 --> 01:09:21.010
that information.

01:09:21.010 --> 01:09:25.640
Actually, if you take our
design class in the spring,

01:09:25.640 --> 01:09:28.140
it gets even worse, because
what you're really in control of

01:09:28.140 --> 01:09:29.590
are the game mechanics.

01:09:29.590 --> 01:09:33.359
And those are going to result in
emergent dynamics-- strategies,

01:09:33.359 --> 01:09:35.830
for instance, things
that are optimal,

01:09:35.830 --> 01:09:38.729
things that are going to lead
people in a downward spiral.

01:09:38.729 --> 01:09:40.441
And that's going to
create an experience

01:09:40.441 --> 01:09:41.899
for the player,
the aesthetic which

01:09:41.899 --> 01:09:45.240
we will get a little bit
into later in the class.

01:09:45.240 --> 01:09:47.770
They're just what the
player actually experiences.

01:09:47.770 --> 01:09:49.250
So the player may
think your game

01:09:49.250 --> 01:09:52.229
is very threatening
and dangerous

01:09:52.229 --> 01:09:55.120
and it's out to get them,
when really to you, it's

01:09:55.120 --> 01:09:59.330
just a perfectly harmless
logic puzzle, because this

01:09:59.330 --> 01:10:01.240
is what you have control over.

01:10:01.240 --> 01:10:03.050
But through all of
that interaction,

01:10:03.050 --> 01:10:06.130
what you've got here is kind
of a second or even third order

01:10:06.130 --> 01:10:09.290
problem, where the
thing that you get,

01:10:09.290 --> 01:10:12.440
where you can actually
create, is not

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:16.770
the thing that the players
are actually experiencing.

01:10:16.770 --> 01:10:19.102
So that's why
you've got to test.

01:10:19.102 --> 01:10:20.810
That's the only way
that you are actually

01:10:20.810 --> 01:10:24.054
going to get information about
what the players are actually

01:10:24.054 --> 01:10:24.595
experiencing.

01:10:24.595 --> 01:10:27.720
You can't intuit it just
by looking at your design.

01:10:27.720 --> 01:10:30.480
Maybe with a lot of
experience, you will eventually

01:10:30.480 --> 01:10:31.900
start to get some
best practices,

01:10:31.900 --> 01:10:33.840
but you still have to
do usability testing,

01:10:33.840 --> 01:10:36.970
even if you're
extremely experienced.

01:10:36.970 --> 01:10:39.220
So one way to do testing
is to actually set

01:10:39.220 --> 01:10:40.310
goals for the player.

01:10:40.310 --> 01:10:43.687
Sometimes when you're doing this
in the middle of play-testing,

01:10:43.687 --> 01:10:45.520
the players can come
up with your own goals.

01:10:45.520 --> 01:10:48.080
But what I like to do
is actually ask players,

01:10:48.080 --> 01:10:52.850
all right, I want you to create
a new game with a new player

01:10:52.850 --> 01:10:55.530
and give it a name
of whatever you want.

01:10:55.530 --> 01:10:57.400
Give them a specific
goal, and see

01:10:57.400 --> 01:11:01.379
how they go about that process
of actually accomplishing that.

01:11:01.379 --> 01:11:03.795
And of course, while they're
doing that, you observe them.

01:11:03.795 --> 01:11:07.410
You encourage them
to talk aloud.

01:11:07.410 --> 01:11:10.530
You observe where they're
moving their mouth,

01:11:10.530 --> 01:11:12.400
or if they're doing a
tablet game, observing

01:11:12.400 --> 01:11:14.590
where the fingers are looking.

01:11:14.590 --> 01:11:17.230
Try to figure out what
they're looking at.

01:11:17.230 --> 01:11:19.600
In big companies they
can do things like eye

01:11:19.600 --> 01:11:22.520
tracking-- Riot Games talks a
little bit about eye tracking--

01:11:22.520 --> 01:11:24.930
to actually figure out
what they're looking at.

01:11:24.930 --> 01:11:27.070
But sometimes if
they're talking aloud,

01:11:27.070 --> 01:11:29.590
they will say, well, I
see all these buttons.

01:11:29.590 --> 01:11:31.520
And they all have icons on them.

01:11:31.520 --> 01:11:35.620
And this one looks like
it might mean delete game,

01:11:35.620 --> 01:11:37.860
so I'm not going
to click on that.

01:11:37.860 --> 01:11:40.780
This one looks
like a disk drive,

01:11:40.780 --> 01:11:43.690
so I think it's a save game, so
I'm not going to click on that.

01:11:43.690 --> 01:11:46.060
And then while they're
saying all of these things,

01:11:46.060 --> 01:11:48.770
you start to understand
how your players actually

01:11:48.770 --> 01:11:51.140
understand the things that
you put into your game.

01:11:51.140 --> 01:11:54.020
And you can figure out why
they're making these errors.

01:11:54.020 --> 01:11:56.420
So you're looking for
them to make these errors,

01:11:56.420 --> 01:11:58.625
and you want to record
them down so that later on,

01:11:58.625 --> 01:12:01.000
when you go back to design
and go back to implementation,

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:01.890
you can fix them.

01:12:01.890 --> 01:12:04.060
Or you can give players
the necessary feedback

01:12:04.060 --> 01:12:06.260
to avoid those kinds of errors.

01:12:06.260 --> 01:12:10.530
But it's important--
when they make an error,

01:12:10.530 --> 01:12:16.000
you have to try to identify what
the player's reaction to that

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:17.370
is.

01:12:17.370 --> 01:12:20.140
Say something happens that
they didn't quite expect.

01:12:20.140 --> 01:12:23.010
Are they surprised,
or are they confused?

01:12:23.010 --> 01:12:25.160
I thought I was
creating a new game,

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:29.490
but I ended up
opening an old game.

01:12:29.490 --> 01:12:32.830
That's probably a
confusion situation.

01:12:32.830 --> 01:12:35.270
I thought this was going
to take out one enemy,

01:12:35.270 --> 01:12:37.940
but it took out five enemies.

01:12:37.940 --> 01:12:42.330
Pretty nice surprise--
players might like that.

01:12:42.330 --> 01:12:47.270
So even though
it's an error, you

01:12:47.270 --> 01:12:51.780
might be able to just live with
that, or even amplify that.

01:12:51.780 --> 01:12:53.910
Let's give these
players these weapons

01:12:53.910 --> 01:12:57.490
that occasionally do critical
damage and surprise the player

01:12:57.490 --> 01:13:01.130
by how bad-ass the players are.

01:13:01.130 --> 01:13:03.630
Are they frustrated,
or are they engaged?

01:13:03.630 --> 01:13:06.787
I chose Flappy Birds in
particular as an example

01:13:06.787 --> 01:13:08.870
here because when people
are playing Flappy Birds,

01:13:08.870 --> 01:13:13.560
they get very angry, right?

01:13:13.560 --> 01:13:16.475
But then they go back
and play it again.

01:13:16.475 --> 01:13:18.110
Are they frustrated?

01:13:18.110 --> 01:13:19.040
Well, yes.

01:13:19.040 --> 01:13:20.290
But are they engaged?

01:13:20.290 --> 01:13:21.790
Yeah, they are.

01:13:21.790 --> 01:13:26.143
For some people, Flappy Birds
is an extremely engaging game,

01:13:26.143 --> 01:13:28.405
and it's kind of a pity
you can't get it anymore.

01:13:28.405 --> 01:13:30.530
I also have two different
versions of Flappy Birds.

01:13:30.530 --> 01:13:32.500
One is kind of an
Arduino powered version,

01:13:32.500 --> 01:13:34.500
but it's really made out
of paper and cardboard.

01:13:34.500 --> 01:13:37.850
And one is the actual digital
version, so to remind you,

01:13:37.850 --> 01:13:41.260
you can do this without
having to actually implement

01:13:41.260 --> 01:13:42.260
a digital version.

01:13:42.260 --> 01:13:44.060
You can do this with
your paper prototype.

01:13:44.060 --> 01:13:47.360
You just have to create a paper
prototype of a user interface

01:13:47.360 --> 01:13:51.204
instead of just game play.

01:13:51.204 --> 01:13:52.870
So you can do testing
even before you've

01:13:52.870 --> 01:13:54.119
written a single line of code.

01:13:56.490 --> 01:13:58.265
So I've talked a lot
about constraints.

01:13:58.265 --> 01:14:00.390
Now, so far everything that
I've been talking about

01:14:00.390 --> 01:14:03.290
has been about
informing the player

01:14:03.290 --> 01:14:05.460
and then trying to
catch those errors

01:14:05.460 --> 01:14:08.310
and then feed that back into
your design of how you provide

01:14:08.310 --> 01:14:09.910
more information to the player.

01:14:09.910 --> 01:14:13.390
But you can also prevent
certain problems.

01:14:13.390 --> 01:14:16.480
Constraints is one way, where
you just make it impossible

01:14:16.480 --> 01:14:21.470
for them to do the wrong thing,
or at least early on, when

01:14:21.470 --> 01:14:23.450
you had multiple choices,
you sort of take some

01:14:23.450 --> 01:14:25.840
of those choices away and
maybe later reintroduce

01:14:25.840 --> 01:14:28.000
those choices when
you are fairly sure

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:30.900
that you've understood what
the consequences of those are.

01:14:30.900 --> 01:14:35.390
You can do conformation,
which is you take an action,

01:14:35.390 --> 01:14:37.230
and then the game asks
you, are you really

01:14:37.230 --> 01:14:39.070
sure you want to do that?

01:14:39.070 --> 01:14:41.948
However, this is
really sub-optimal.

01:14:41.948 --> 01:14:43.370
Any idea why?

01:14:46.220 --> 01:14:49.580
Why is it bad to get a little
dialogue box asking you,

01:14:49.580 --> 01:14:51.628
are you sure you
want to do this?

01:14:51.628 --> 01:14:53.504
AUDIENCE: If you
wanted to get to it,

01:14:53.504 --> 01:14:55.037
it might be really annoying.

01:14:55.037 --> 01:14:55.620
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:14:55.620 --> 01:14:56.690
It gets annoying, yeah.

01:14:56.690 --> 01:15:00.157
AUDIENCE: And it might
make you doubt what you

01:15:00.157 --> 01:15:01.510
were doing in the first place.

01:15:01.510 --> 01:15:02.093
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:15:02.093 --> 01:15:05.410
Are you really sure you
want to close this web page?

01:15:05.410 --> 01:15:09.410
You really sure that you
want to save this game.

01:15:09.410 --> 01:15:14.520
Well, maybe not, but maybe
that was the right thing to do.

01:15:14.520 --> 01:15:16.810
You can also get really
automated on that.

01:15:16.810 --> 01:15:20.770
Players can sort of learn
to just click yes every time

01:15:20.770 --> 01:15:25.290
that thing pops up, and then
kit kind of defeats its purpose.

01:15:25.290 --> 01:15:27.630
If all you're doing is
throwing up a dialogue box

01:15:27.630 --> 01:15:30.980
and they're going to say every
minute or something like that,

01:15:30.980 --> 01:15:33.280
and the answer 90%
percent of the time

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:37.130
is yes, then players start
to learn to just click

01:15:37.130 --> 01:15:38.824
yes every time they
see the dialog box,

01:15:38.824 --> 01:15:41.240
whether or not they actually
intended to click yes or not.

01:15:41.240 --> 01:15:42.770
And that's bad.

01:15:42.770 --> 01:15:44.570
You're training them
to sort of defeat

01:15:44.570 --> 01:15:45.899
the confirmation process.

01:15:45.899 --> 01:15:47.565
And then you get
dialog boxes like this.

01:15:55.180 --> 01:15:57.035
I don't know what
the buttons do.

01:16:01.530 --> 01:16:07.590
So this is Skype, obviously.

01:16:07.590 --> 01:16:10.920
This itself can be so
confusing for players.

01:16:10.920 --> 01:16:14.480
The confirmation dialog itself
is a piece of user interface

01:16:14.480 --> 01:16:16.980
that can go right
and can go wrong.

01:16:16.980 --> 01:16:19.920
So you've just
introduced a new element

01:16:19.920 --> 01:16:23.090
that can be misinterpreted
in the design of the game.

01:16:23.090 --> 01:16:26.670
So confirmation is something
that exists, is often used,

01:16:26.670 --> 01:16:30.210
and can backfire, and we need to
be aware that it can backfire.

01:16:30.210 --> 01:16:32.050
You can also do checks.

01:16:32.050 --> 01:16:37.640
If you've ever entered a code
into Xbox Live or PlayStation

01:16:37.640 --> 01:16:43.420
network or the Apple
App Store, the numbers

01:16:43.420 --> 01:16:45.800
that you're typing
into the system

01:16:45.800 --> 01:16:51.940
have to fit some sort of
checksum or error correction

01:16:51.940 --> 01:16:53.070
protocol.

01:16:53.070 --> 01:16:55.320
And you can prevent
certain errors

01:16:55.320 --> 01:16:58.750
by doing checks on the
data that you're entering.

01:16:58.750 --> 01:17:00.730
Now, this is probably
very familiar for anyone

01:17:00.730 --> 01:17:03.260
who's done any kind of user
interface, software engineering

01:17:03.260 --> 01:17:03.950
class.

01:17:03.950 --> 01:17:07.170
But this is one from
Microsoft Xbox Love.

01:17:07.170 --> 01:17:09.040
And if you type
in a code that you

01:17:09.040 --> 01:17:14.200
might have gotten from a
giveaway or a free coupon

01:17:14.200 --> 01:17:17.260
from a game developer,
or maybe a card

01:17:17.260 --> 01:17:19.110
that you bought at
the store, they're

01:17:19.110 --> 01:17:21.310
always 25 characters long.

01:17:21.310 --> 01:17:24.810
They're always separated by
these dashes in chunks of five.

01:17:24.810 --> 01:17:26.420
I don't have to type
those dashes in.

01:17:26.420 --> 01:17:28.680
I just start typing, and
those dashes fill themselves

01:17:28.680 --> 01:17:30.010
in automatically.

01:17:30.010 --> 01:17:35.220
If I do type the dash, the input
box will just ignore the dash,

01:17:35.220 --> 01:17:39.230
and it will only allow me to
enter in those characters.

01:17:39.230 --> 01:17:42.360
So that makes sure that
the dashes are always

01:17:42.360 --> 01:17:45.550
exactly five characters
apart from each other.

01:17:45.550 --> 01:17:47.180
And that's a visual
way to provide

01:17:47.180 --> 01:17:51.900
a check while I'm entering
this long string of characters.

01:17:51.900 --> 01:17:53.590
I can do this sort
of visual check

01:17:53.590 --> 01:17:57.890
of, are my characters
appearing in the right position

01:17:57.890 --> 01:18:01.370
in the string as they
are printed on my card,

01:18:01.370 --> 01:18:04.724
and as it is being
displayed on my screen.

01:18:04.724 --> 01:18:06.140
You can do other
kinds of checks--

01:18:06.140 --> 01:18:10.240
like, if you try to do the same
thing on the Apple App Store,

01:18:10.240 --> 01:18:12.810
I believe it could be
numbers, it could be letters,

01:18:12.810 --> 01:18:16.600
or whatever, but you can hit
OK as soon as you enter it in,

01:18:16.600 --> 01:18:19.420
and the system actually does
a quick check before it even

01:18:19.420 --> 01:18:23.010
sends the code off to Apple
on whether that's actually

01:18:23.010 --> 01:18:26.390
a valid string, that fits
a certain kind of checksum

01:18:26.390 --> 01:18:27.027
algorithm.

01:18:27.027 --> 01:18:28.360
Before it sends it off to Apple.

01:18:28.360 --> 01:18:29.830
And if it's a wrong one, it
just tells you right away,

01:18:29.830 --> 01:18:31.380
no, you actually made an error.

01:18:31.380 --> 01:18:32.256
You can fix that now.

01:18:32.256 --> 01:18:34.338
So you don't have to wait
for it to hit the server

01:18:34.338 --> 01:18:34.930
and come back.

01:18:37.550 --> 01:18:39.755
But say the error does happen.

01:18:39.755 --> 01:18:41.690
The player has made
a mistake, and it

01:18:41.690 --> 01:18:45.010
happens to be a mistake that
you know about as a designer.

01:18:45.010 --> 01:18:47.190
And you know this mistake
is going to come up often.

01:18:47.190 --> 01:18:49.220
This kind of error
is going to happen.

01:18:49.220 --> 01:18:51.770
And maybe it's a slip,
maybe it's a mistake.

01:18:51.770 --> 01:18:55.370
And you want to
provide some feedback.

01:18:55.370 --> 01:18:58.430
So first of all, make sure that
you are informing the player

01:18:58.430 --> 01:18:59.877
that an error has happened.

01:18:59.877 --> 01:19:02.210
And you need to test whether
the information that you're

01:19:02.210 --> 01:19:04.500
providing, whether
it's audio or visual,

01:19:04.500 --> 01:19:07.900
some combination of the
two, is actually something

01:19:07.900 --> 01:19:10.420
that people notice
and see, and then they

01:19:10.420 --> 01:19:12.740
realize that, oh, I've
made a mistake somewhere.

01:19:12.740 --> 01:19:14.490
And then you've got
to get them some tools

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:16.700
to be able to fix that problem.

01:19:16.700 --> 01:19:18.900
There's backwards,
which is basically undo.

01:19:18.900 --> 01:19:21.980
This is Words With
Friends, for instance.

01:19:21.980 --> 01:19:25.090
If you enter in
some sort of word--

01:19:25.090 --> 01:19:27.022
this is an online
game, by the way.

01:19:27.022 --> 01:19:29.230
It's a multi-player game
that you play on your phone.

01:19:29.230 --> 01:19:31.167
And because it's
Words With Friends,

01:19:31.167 --> 01:19:33.250
you're basically playing
Scrabble against somebody

01:19:33.250 --> 01:19:36.110
who's geographically
separated from you.

01:19:36.110 --> 01:19:39.679
And if you've taken a turn,
you've entered in a word.

01:19:39.679 --> 01:19:41.220
And then you say,
wait a minute, I've

01:19:41.220 --> 01:19:42.810
come up with a better word.

01:19:42.810 --> 01:19:43.750
You can hit Undo.

01:19:43.750 --> 01:19:45.590
I think it's called Recall.

01:19:45.590 --> 01:19:47.480
The button is actually
called Recall.

01:19:47.480 --> 01:19:49.450
Take your move
back and then just

01:19:49.450 --> 01:19:51.470
replay your turn
before the other person

01:19:51.470 --> 01:19:52.780
has taken their turn.

01:19:52.780 --> 01:19:55.190
But that's backwards
error recovery,

01:19:55.190 --> 01:19:58.160
very good for things
like turn-based games,

01:19:58.160 --> 01:20:01.920
games that you play by
email for instance or games

01:20:01.920 --> 01:20:07.620
that you are sort of--
like Final Fantasy Tactics,

01:20:07.620 --> 01:20:08.680
or strategy games.

01:20:08.680 --> 01:20:11.560
A lot of strategy games
which are turn-based

01:20:11.560 --> 01:20:14.640
allow you to sort of
undo your decisions.

01:20:14.640 --> 01:20:16.176
Even if you've
said, yes, this is

01:20:16.176 --> 01:20:17.550
what I want to
do, wait a minute,

01:20:17.550 --> 01:20:18.800
this is not what I want to do.

01:20:18.800 --> 01:20:20.870
I want to undo that.

01:20:20.870 --> 01:20:22.660
There's also forward
error recovery.

01:20:22.660 --> 01:20:28.990
This is a screenshot of
Mario where Mario's mid-jump,

01:20:28.990 --> 01:20:31.361
and based on player
experience up to this point,

01:20:31.361 --> 01:20:32.860
you realize halfway
through the jump

01:20:32.860 --> 01:20:34.985
that you're not going to
be able to make that jump.

01:20:34.985 --> 01:20:36.020
What can Mario do?

01:20:38.455 --> 01:20:39.330
You can go backwards.

01:20:39.330 --> 01:20:41.880
You can change
direction in midair

01:20:41.880 --> 01:20:44.330
and say, oop, not
what I'm going to do.

01:20:44.330 --> 01:20:45.420
It doesn't rewind time.

01:20:45.420 --> 01:20:46.961
You're still moving
time in the game.

01:20:46.961 --> 01:20:49.410
And time is important
in a Mario game.

01:20:49.410 --> 01:20:52.290
But the player has the tool to
say, I'm going to try to jump.

01:20:52.290 --> 01:20:54.110
No, I'm not going to
complete this jump.

01:20:54.110 --> 01:20:57.870
I'm going to go backwards
before it's too late.

01:20:57.870 --> 01:21:00.850
There is a consequence to that,
and the player is losing time.

01:21:00.850 --> 01:21:03.070
And in many of
your games, you're

01:21:03.070 --> 01:21:06.400
going to want to allow those
errors to happen but then

01:21:06.400 --> 01:21:10.420
give players tools to be able to
take a new action to compensate

01:21:10.420 --> 01:21:13.320
for the mistake of
the previous action.

01:21:13.320 --> 01:21:17.730
And that is called
forward error recovery.

01:21:17.730 --> 01:21:22.660
Now, if it's a mistake that
happens near the end of a game

01:21:22.660 --> 01:21:25.500
session-- say you're
making a multi-player game

01:21:25.500 --> 01:21:28.540
and somebody's about to win.

01:21:28.540 --> 01:21:30.350
Forward error recovery
may not be something

01:21:30.350 --> 01:21:33.270
that you want to make too
easy, because somebody's

01:21:33.270 --> 01:21:35.380
spent a long time actually
getting themselves

01:21:35.380 --> 01:21:37.820
in a position where
they can win the game.

01:21:37.820 --> 01:21:40.870
And then the person who's losing
uses whatever forward error

01:21:40.870 --> 01:21:45.180
recovery tools you've given
them to say, ah, let me just

01:21:45.180 --> 01:21:46.750
take back all of
those mistakes I did

01:21:46.750 --> 01:21:48.817
and then come back from behind.

01:21:48.817 --> 01:21:51.275
Well, if you were explicitly
designing a game where someone

01:21:51.275 --> 01:21:53.274
is supposed to be able
to come back from behind,

01:21:53.274 --> 01:21:56.254
like Mario Kart does something
like that, then that's great.

01:21:56.254 --> 01:21:58.170
But if you're trying to
make some sort of game

01:21:58.170 --> 01:22:01.330
where long-term strategy is
supposed to pay off, then yeah,

01:22:01.330 --> 01:22:03.750
you don't want to make
those forward recovery

01:22:03.750 --> 01:22:05.995
tools too powerful.

01:22:05.995 --> 01:22:07.495
Let people live
with their mistakes.

01:22:14.074 --> 01:22:15.740
One last point, and
I save this for last

01:22:15.740 --> 01:22:17.573
because I want you to
be thinking about this

01:22:17.573 --> 01:22:19.320
in your team, so
something for you

01:22:19.320 --> 01:22:21.900
to go into discussion
about after this talk,

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:23.680
is accessibility.

01:22:23.680 --> 01:22:26.730
One challenge is that
when people think,

01:22:26.730 --> 01:22:33.270
my game is for everyone, my game
is for anybody who plays games,

01:22:33.270 --> 01:22:37.430
is that that's not actually
what the game ends up being.

01:22:37.430 --> 01:22:41.150
Often it becomes
this, which is you're

01:22:41.150 --> 01:22:46.250
going to assume that your
player is focused and has

01:22:46.250 --> 01:22:51.540
full use of their hands
and full visual acuity,

01:22:51.540 --> 01:22:53.380
that they speak
English so they'll

01:22:53.380 --> 01:22:55.500
understand any text
that you give them,

01:22:55.500 --> 01:22:57.790
that they know how to
install stuff in a computer

01:22:57.790 --> 01:23:00.650
and they've played games
before, that they are around

01:23:00.650 --> 01:23:04.287
about your age, that they
have desktop computers that

01:23:04.287 --> 01:23:06.870
have lots of processing power,
especially if you're doing a 3D

01:23:06.870 --> 01:23:10.100
game, that their mice have more
than one button, that they're

01:23:10.100 --> 01:23:11.840
actually using mice
and not a trackpad,

01:23:11.840 --> 01:23:13.620
that they've got
headphones so they're

01:23:13.620 --> 01:23:15.654
going to listen
to every audio cut

01:23:15.654 --> 01:23:18.350
that you're going to give
them without distraction.

01:23:22.450 --> 01:23:25.750
So these particular
red line things

01:23:25.750 --> 01:23:30.130
are the things that I want
you to be willing to question

01:23:30.130 --> 01:23:31.440
about your own game.

01:23:31.440 --> 01:23:33.360
There are some things
like-- they're speaking,

01:23:33.360 --> 01:23:34.700
computer-literate young adults.

01:23:37.500 --> 01:23:40.210
It's great to be able to
design games for people

01:23:40.210 --> 01:23:41.960
who are not like you.

01:23:41.960 --> 01:23:45.750
It is a little bit beyond the
scope of this particular class,

01:23:45.750 --> 01:23:48.850
although you do have to keep in
mind that we are also designing

01:23:48.850 --> 01:23:51.330
this games, your
final fourth project,

01:23:51.330 --> 01:23:55.300
for people who may be working
for the Red Cross Red Crescent

01:23:55.300 --> 01:23:56.370
Climate Centre.

01:23:56.370 --> 01:24:01.500
So you want to keep them in
mind and consider-- many of them

01:24:01.500 --> 01:24:02.800
actually speak English.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:05.040
They may be
foreigners, people who

01:24:05.040 --> 01:24:09.035
work in other countries, who
will appreciate a game that

01:24:09.035 --> 01:24:13.101
is a little bit more language
agnostic or even localized

01:24:13.101 --> 01:24:13.600
for them.

01:24:16.507 --> 01:24:18.090
Shall we assume that
the computers are

01:24:18.090 --> 01:24:20.610
capable of handling your game?

01:24:20.610 --> 01:24:23.450
OK, I think for this
class that's all right.

01:24:23.450 --> 01:24:27.350
But shall we assume that
the computers are only

01:24:27.350 --> 01:24:29.970
running your game and nothing
else, that they're not

01:24:29.970 --> 01:24:33.131
running any IM clients--
or a lot of the games

01:24:33.131 --> 01:24:34.880
are going to be browser
games so that they

01:24:34.880 --> 01:24:38.090
don't have any other browser
windows open, for instance.

01:24:38.090 --> 01:24:42.331
I think that might be asking
too much of your player.

01:24:42.331 --> 01:24:44.830
You might want to assume that
they have other things running

01:24:44.830 --> 01:24:48.410
around in the background-- their
iTunes playlist, for instance--

01:24:48.410 --> 01:24:51.390
and which is going to
interfere with your sound.

01:24:51.390 --> 01:24:55.570
You should be able to design
your game so that you don't

01:24:55.570 --> 01:24:58.240
assume everyone has a left
mouse button and a right mouse

01:24:58.240 --> 01:25:00.012
button, or necessarily a mouse.

01:25:00.012 --> 01:25:01.720
For one thing, it'll
make testing easier.

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:03.380
A couple of you
discovered last time

01:25:03.380 --> 01:25:05.630
you did a visual test, that
if you don't have a mouse,

01:25:05.630 --> 01:25:07.969
a lot of your games actually
became difficult to play.

01:25:07.969 --> 01:25:10.010
You might want to have
that discussion-- at least

01:25:10.010 --> 01:25:12.490
have that discussion with
your team, and if you decide,

01:25:12.490 --> 01:25:15.637
no, a mouse is essential,
make it very, very clear

01:25:15.637 --> 01:25:16.720
that's what you're saying.

01:25:16.720 --> 01:25:18.780
And put it in your game.

01:25:18.780 --> 01:25:22.230
Say, this game is best played
with a mouse and headphones.

01:25:22.230 --> 01:25:25.160
There's a lot of iOS games out
there that require headphones,

01:25:25.160 --> 01:25:26.880
and they will state
right upfront,

01:25:26.880 --> 01:25:28.960
this game is best
played with headphones.

01:25:32.100 --> 01:25:38.960
And I would like you to at
least consider colorblindness.

01:25:38.960 --> 01:25:42.860
Actually, yeah, there we go.

01:25:42.860 --> 01:25:45.410
When you are designing
art for your game,

01:25:45.410 --> 01:25:47.010
buttons that need
to be distinguished

01:25:47.010 --> 01:25:49.165
from each under or
visual cues, consider

01:25:49.165 --> 01:25:51.290
that there are people who
can't tell the difference

01:25:51.290 --> 01:25:53.550
between certain color pairings.

01:25:53.550 --> 01:25:54.570
What are common ones?

01:25:54.570 --> 01:25:57.470
Red, green.

01:25:57.470 --> 01:25:57.970
Red, blue?

01:25:57.970 --> 01:25:58.928
AUDIENCE: Blue, yellow.

01:25:58.928 --> 01:26:00.340
PROFESSOR: Oh, blue, yellow.

01:26:00.340 --> 01:26:03.210
And red, blue.

01:26:03.210 --> 01:26:03.735
Red, blue.

01:26:03.735 --> 01:26:05.600
Blue, yellow.

01:26:05.600 --> 01:26:06.469
And red, green.

01:26:06.469 --> 01:26:08.510
Those are the most common
ones, but there's a lot

01:26:08.510 --> 01:26:10.460
of colorblindness out there.

01:26:10.460 --> 01:26:14.410
And it affects, I think,
20% of the population.

01:26:14.410 --> 01:26:15.162
10?

01:26:15.162 --> 01:26:15.927
10 to 20%?

01:26:15.927 --> 01:26:18.260
AUDIENCE: I think it's as
much as 10% of the population.

01:26:18.260 --> 01:26:19.890
PROFESSOR: 10% of
the population.

01:26:19.890 --> 01:26:21.490
So there's a lot
of people out there

01:26:21.490 --> 01:26:24.466
who might well want to
be playing your game

01:26:24.466 --> 01:26:26.840
but can't because they can't
tell apart those visual cues

01:26:26.840 --> 01:26:27.840
that you're giving them.

01:26:27.840 --> 01:26:30.550
So make sure that they're also
taking advantage of things

01:26:30.550 --> 01:26:33.330
like shape and brightness.

01:26:33.330 --> 01:26:36.820
These are things where if
somebody is colorblind,

01:26:36.820 --> 01:26:39.490
they can at least
still distinguish shape

01:26:39.490 --> 01:26:40.430
from each other.

01:26:40.430 --> 01:26:43.470
So instead of having red
diamonds and blue diamonds,

01:26:43.470 --> 01:26:46.740
you have red diamonds and
blue stars or something,

01:26:46.740 --> 01:26:51.020
and that makes it easier to
tell that there's a difference.

01:26:51.020 --> 01:26:53.960
I mentioned other application
windows, touch pads,

01:26:53.960 --> 01:26:56.480
or the possibility that somebody
might be playing your game

01:26:56.480 --> 01:26:58.390
